<br>
But although the simplicity of flat income tax is  appealing to me I think it has some problems.  First off, our current tax system gives incentives for things like home ownership, having kids, taking care of elderly or disabled people among other things.  <br>
<br>
What would happen to the price of real estate if owning your own home wasn't a tax incentive?  I think it might plummet.  If people rent more, what will happen to neighborhoods?  High home ownership means people with a vested interest in keeping neighborhoods nice, whereas lots of renters tend to make property values go down.<br>
<br>
I don't know what the solution is.  Maybe it's a national sales tax?  That might encourage people to save more money too.  Then at least you'd be taxing the biggest spenders the most.   Nicest part about it is there's no bloody tax forms and the IRS could burn in hell! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/bdrinal28133.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dirrabey>Dirra Bey</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>No Life</span><br>  Posts: 3085<br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/3/03 2:39:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub28.ezboard.com/fdrinal28133frm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2042.topic&index=34>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: .....</span><hr size=1> Those are really good points, and go a long way to explaining why we prolly won't get a simple flat tax any time soon -- every special interest has a hand in the cookie jar, ranging from homeowners to Humvee owners to oil companies to retired people to poor people who actually pay negative income taxes in many cases (EIC).<br>
