<br>
Actually there's nothing contradictory in that statement. It means that although some conservatives come from the point of view that there is a moral or religious imperative to have government do or not do certain things, in the end, there's little conflict between the end result that most conservatives want and the goals of libertarians (small l). As I recall, the context of the quote was an article on the role of libertarians in the GOP and whether or not there was some sort of disconnect when libertarians join the coalition -- an assertion that is silly on it's face, for the reasons stated. Yes, there are social conservatives that would like to regulate your bedroom activity; they are a very very small minority in the party and will remain so. The Queer lobby in the DNC is also a small minority; does that negate the DLC?<br>
<br>
Since you asked, were it up to me, I would never &quot;require&quot; anyone to say the Pledge. At the same time, I think it's important that children be instructed in patriotism and respect for the flag and the Republic and hundreds of thousands of lives lost that it represents. Course, what that has to do with the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>brilliant</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> quote you dug up, I have no idea. <br>
<br>
And before you go there, I see nothing contradictory in someone being pro-life and still being a libertarian. After all, the ultimate right is that of life. Some may argue over when it begins, but that's a whole nother thread.<br>
